Separate Realities<br><br>
We all live in separate realities, we know that women look at things differently then men do. That is because we interpret things differently. Spatz reacts like a dog, which knows he has defecated in the wrong place. You yell at the dog and he sticks his tail in between his legs and runs away but for only a short distance. He then forgets why you yelled at him and comes back wagging his tail with the ball in his mouth wanting to play again. The problem is spatz doesn’t understand that we don’t want to play with him because the ball he’s carrying in his mouth is full of dog shit, none the less he wants you to throw it and play with him. Some people learn from their past experiences others do not. Spatz maybe the exception, I don’t know.<br><br>
I believe everyone else sees through the filters of their own interpretations learned through our life’s journey. We respond through the filters of our own individual unique memories, beliefs, traditions, family and religious experiences. They all contribute to who we are, what we have done and what we will do if provoked a certain way as well as how we will react when presented with certain outside stimuli’s.<br><br>
In Nam the gooks knew this and we knew it. They would open up and we would hit the deck. I even remember once as the bullets started to fly and as I’m diving for cover behind a rice paddy dike. I’m thinking; <br>
“Hey, I’ve done this before, stimulus equals response. Just like my science had said and yesterdays battle experience taught me.<br><br>
We all also understand the world all around us by these learned experiences, and react by those recessed experiences. They are valid to us because they have been validated by our past experiences. Once a commie, always a commie. <br>
My recent Dentist chair experience (I believe God allowed Communist and Dentist to come out of the same mold), as the dentist drilled inside my mouth, the burning drill grinding away at the bone coupled with the smell of hot blood in my mouth brought back a flashback of Napalm burning flesh and bones in the trenches and open rice paddies of Vietnam, it was a mini-flashback.<br><br>
Now, there’s another misconception, or is it. Do we have long drawn out flashbacks as the movies depict or just quick mini-flashbacks? I don’t believe I’ve ever had a flashback that has lasted longer then a mini-micro second. Something, said, done or seen has triggered them, but they have not all been recollection of only bad experiences. <br><br>
There is much we can discuss here, what triggers what responses?<br>

